  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ComponentListener, ImageObserver, MenuContainer, Serializable, EventListener, Accessible, AnimatedVisualisationListener, AnimatedVisualisationProvider, TimelineObject, Visualisation<Video<MBFImage>>, VisualisationImageProvider
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ShotBoundaryVideoBarVisualisation, VideoObjectVisualisation

    public abstract class VideoBarVisualisation
extends TimelineObjectAdapter<Video<MBFImage>>
implements AnimatedVisualisationProvider
    Displays a block, or bar, which represents the data. The block will be scaled to fit the JPanel in which its drawn. The block will contain a visImage of the data content. The visImage of the content is determined by one of the subclasses of this class.

    This class will process the data in a separate thread. Obviously, it's not sensible to call this class with a "live" data stream, such as from a VideoCapture object.

      • update

        public void update()
        If you override this method, you should call it at the end of your own implementation. Called to update the visualisation. This method can expect the visImage member to be available and of the correct size. The method simply needs to draw the visualisation to this MBFImage. You should wrap any drawing code in a synchronized block, synchronized on the visImage - this stops the image being repainted to the screen half way through drawing.

        Update is called from the paint() method so should ideally not force a repaint() as this will call a continuous repaint loop.

        Specified by:
        update in class VisualisationImpl<Video<MBFImage>>
        See Also:
        VisualisationImpl.update()
